{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17654977","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17654977"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:57:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:57:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18643"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18643","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18643"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.23,0.03,0.06,0.65]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11375"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80315"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11375","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11375"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18643"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65583"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4904"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"6678"},{"type":"tags","id":"7108"},{"type":"tags","id":"7111"},{"type":"tags","id":"7112"},{"type":"tags","id":"11375"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26388"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26650"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80315","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80315"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe dural venous sinuses are important channels that drain blood from the brain. They are formed between layers of dura mater and contain no valves.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the normal venous drainage pathway from the cerebrum?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Straight sinus drains directly into internal jugular vein","Superior sagittal sinus drains directly into sigmoid sinus","Great cerebral vein drains directly into transverse sinus","Transverse sinus drains into superior sagittal sinus","Superior sagittal sinus drains into confluence of sinuses"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esuperior sagittal sinus drains into the confluence of sinuses\u003C/strong\u003E at the internal occipital protuberance (image). This is the normal pathway for venous drainage from the superior aspect of the cerebrum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Estraight sinus drains directly into internal jugular vein\u003C/strong\u003E - The straight sinus drains into the confluence of sinuses\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esuperior sagittal sinus drains directly into sigmoid sinus\u003C/strong\u003E - The superior sagittal sinus must first drain into the confluence of sinuses\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Egreat cerebral vein drains directly into transverse sinus\u003C/strong\u003E - The great cerebral vein combines with the inferior sagittal sinus to create the straight sinus\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Etransverse sinus drains into superior sagittal sinus\u003C/strong\u003E - Blood flows in the opposite direction; transverse sinuses receive blood from the confluence of sinuses\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFrom the confluence of sinuses, blood flows laterally through the transverse sinuses, then through the sigmoid sinuses, and finally into the internal jugular veins.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The superior sagittal sinus drains into the confluence of sinuses at the internal occipital protuberance.","The straight sinus is formed by the union of the great cerebral vein and inferior sagittal sinus.","The transverse sinuses drain blood from the confluence of sinuses laterally towards the sigmoid sinuses."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","\u201cThe major venous sinuses and their tributaries\u201d by P. K. Sasidharan\u00a0is licensed under\u00a0Creative Commons Attribution-Share Alike 3.0 Unported license. (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/3.0). \u003Chttps://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Major_venous_sinuses_and_their_tributaries.png\u003E"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65583"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18643"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21431"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21431","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21431"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/APSjyBwL2F6TlmtcG4rknnkfRRKofz.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/APSjyBwL2F6TlmtcG4rknnkfRRKofz.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":549}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65583","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65583"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-20T12:49:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-20T12:50:05+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11375"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80315"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags